column56: Having a processing tool that can handle the large data-sets from high resolution platform is key, currently this is our biggest restraint.having a tool that can be routinely applied to our investigations in a rapid, robust and automated manner will significantly increase our output. This is huge when we think about turnaround times for investigations and publications.Having a database that includes more of the ions relative to each ionisation mode is important. For example, most databases are tailored towards ESI and thus miss many of the ions formed by MALDI, which slows down processing as everything has to be mined by hand. Most databases include the [M+H]+, [M+Na]+ and the [M+K]+, but none have the fragment ions that are commonly observed, such as [M-CH3]-. Having an algorithm that sums the ions/adducts of the same species is also important for clinical/disease state comparisons, as people often report changes in species when there aren't any changes, and it is actually changes in the sodium and potassium content.
